step.context:
\text{Given the conditions, if there are x packages of nuts}\\
\text{and y packages of bolts being produced each day,}\\
\text{what do we need to maximise?}

step.tex:
\text{We need to maximise Total Profit} = T(x, y),\\
\begin{align}
\qquad T(x, y) &= x(pkgs/day)\cdot 17.50(Rs/pkg) +
    y(pkgs/day)\cdot 7.00(Rs/pkg) \\
\implies T(x, y) &= 17.50x + 7.00y
\end{align}

\text{We need to maximise Total Profit} = T(x, y),\\
\begin{align}
\qquad T(x, y) &= x/12(pkgs/day)\cdot 17.50(Rs/pkg) +
    y/12(pkgs/day)\cdot 7.00(Rs/pkg) \\
\implies T(x, y) &= 17.50/12 x + 7.00/12 y
\end{align}

step.context:
\text{For the above constraints, what does the plot }\\
\text{representing the feasible region and its corner }\\
\text{points look like?}

\text{Can we predict the number of each type of package}\\
\text{that needs to be producted in order to maximise profit}\\
\text{based on the corner points in the diagram above?}

step.reason:
\text{Since the feasible region is bounded, we can}\\
\text{establish the maximum by substituting corner} \\
\text{points in the objective function.}
